text: I use this with the XM Redmi 4a  and am most impressed with how the app has enabled to control all of my Lounge's devices from my phone.   1.  Sony LCD TV (KLD-40E400) 2.  Sony AV Receiver (STR-DH510) 3.  Multichoice Pace Cable Set-top box (TDS850).  Have customised all the remotes in the app to look like the original remotes  and have a unified smart remote that has a selection of mostly used functions from each of the above devices' remotes (e.g have dedicated channel buttons to access a channel -e.g channel 203 (set-top) just but a touch of a single button, HDMI SYNC MENU (TV),  sound field adjustment buttons (receiver)...  I further have created remotes for: 1.  iogear wireless 3D HD transmitter kit. 2.  Optima video projector which both enjoy full remote functionality.  All in all I am a very happy chap.  You need to have a good imagination to have it all pieced nicely together.  Well done to the Developer(s).  6 out of 5....

I use another app called remote for Android for that, but this app and that app seem to conflict so I have to leave that one uninstalled until I need it. text: Absolutely terrible.   Could not even get a remote set up without being bombarded with annoying video ads that you can't close for several seconds.     Once I finally got the remote set up it randomly would stop working.  Oddly enough all of the ads would play perfectly fine!  At one point I put it down for a couple minutes to grab a beverage and when I came back about there were 4 or 5 ads stacked on top of each other trying to play video ads.  Closing one revealed another, closing that one revealed another hiding behind it and so on.   The app locked up again shortly after that (it locks up a lot and runs very sluggish).  I noticed after restarting my tablet it'd added itself to the main unlock screen and my tablet was running horribly.    Uninstalled it immediately.  I already had doubts about it due to the permissions that it requires.  There any reason it needs access to my photos, the ability to make in store purchases on my behalf, allow draw over OTHER apps, and most of the other permissions it claims to need?   If the free version is this horrible the paid version is likely not worth it.

appTitle: AnyMote Universal Remote + WiFi Smart Home Control
AnyMote Universal Remote + WiFi Smart Home Control
text: This is the best remote application out there. The only one I have found that offers a one-time purchase of the software. Most others are monthly subscription basis, and that just eliminates ads. None of them offer full-on customization of remotes as this one does. I played with it for about 30 minutes, dropped the $7 to buy it outright and have not looked back. Would suggest it to anyone looking for a fully featured remote application. I now have one remote for each room that controls all the devices in that room and love everything about it. For people complaining about purchasing to use without ads, try Sure Remote... You have to subscribe for $0.99 a month to remove them, so after 7 months you could've just bought this one and been able to design your own remotes. For those complaining about missing devices, if you report in-app that you can't find a suitable remote you will likely get a reply. Not sure what the gentleman was on about saying it was 89 bucks to upgrade... It's $6.99 US dollars. It's an application that someone had to sit down and develop. That takes time, and time costs money. It looks better than the other apps on the market (I've downloaded the other two "good" ones), it's the only one of the big three that you can buy outright without a subscription (why subscribe to something for a dollar a month when you can buy something for $7???). And it's the only one I can find that allows you to create and combine custom remotes.

My sole complaint would be the inability to use this app on phones that are not IR capable as I would really like to use it on my car phone. UPDATE 120418: Changing my review from 1 Star to 4. As I accidentally came to understand this app better, found that the only time the app is prepared to kill unnecessary background apps is when the device is not being charged. That is when the button to kill apps turns green, showing ready for use. This app can use significant power when overriding other apps to shut them down, but to be fair, I don't think that can be helped. I only wish this app had the option to continually monitor & kill unnecessary apps, ALL the time rather than needing manual prompting. Nevertheless, it accomplishes its advertised purpose; you just have to keep an eye on it and keep pushing the button every time it turns green, if you want to keep the other apps dormant. ********* The only thing that works in this app is the battery life notification. The 'button' to kill background apps doesn't work, nor does the app do this itself anyway. When first installed received a notice that so many apps we're stopped, then nothing. It gives you the option to opt out certain apps from being stopped, but no indicators of what's running it what's been stopped. If for some insane reason your phone doesn't have a battery life advisor in the notification bar, this would work well. Just don't depend on it for killing background apps or providing information to that effect.

text:
This app does nothing except point out ways for you to save battery. Look 
them up online and save yourself the trouble of downloading a pointless app.

appTitle: Battery Doctor-Battery Life Saver & Battery Cooler
text:
I'm not really sure if this app does what it says it does. I did not notice 
any appreciable difference. What I did notice is that the second I started 
this app more than 20 internet transactions occurred. And that happened 
before I was able to shut off its internet access. Now why would it want 
internet access but not list it in the permissions? I could understand a 
couple of Internet request to see if there's something new you need. But 
the amount of internet activity suggests something more along the lines of 
data mining. I can't prove that. I can only prove that it accesses the 
internet a lot. I have check the permissions access list located at the 
very bottom of the Google store app page. This app want so many permissions 
that it simply does not need. To me that suggests this app is doing some 
data mining. It may do what it says it does, but it also does a lot more 
you may not want.

text: So I'll start by saying I got this app to 1 - see which apps are using up the most battery, and 2 - to try and prolong my battery life. The app to me feels almost like some sort of Chinese scam app. A lot of stuff is in broken English and half the features don't really seem to do anything (such as optimizing your phone, it will always say there's issues even if you scanned 1 minute ago. Just as well I cannot see which apps are draining my battery, so the app is virtually useless. But I have yet to mention the worst feature yet, the ads. They are so intrusive, and I'm not talking about just when you have the app open, though there is plenty of that. Imagine you get off work, pull your phone out and unlock it, and you're greeted with ads that you have to close before you can actually use your phone. It's a really nice feature. I think I'll spend 3 dollars on the other battery app that doesn't make my phone feel like it's got a virus on it.

For instance I terminate an app called iCam and then open Battery Saver but it's not there. I have to close and reopen Battery Saver a few times or wait several minutes for it to appear.  After it finally appears I click Stop app and it kills it. But then, after its done and I click OK, it reappears and has to be killed all over again. text: Initiates a background TCP scan to port 80 of all IPs in your network (WiFI subnet) whenever you power on your device, even if the app hasn't been opened. In my opinion this is undisclosed behaviour that isn't necessary for functionality and may be data collection for evil purposes (may be sending the list to servers in a foreign country, could be used for tracking, identifying potential hacking targets etc.). The scan can be seen f.e. by OS Monitor. Do not recommend.

text: I have an older Acer TV/monitor in my bedroom that the remote died. This is the only app that would actually make it turn on. I only took a star of because there is no way to change the input from the app. Therefore, Even though I mostly use HDMI1 input, I still have to push the button on the television when I need another input. The app itself does not use much resources and does not drain my battery any faster. I have had NO issues with ads in the app. It does the basic channel changes and volume controls as well as the power. The default settings are good with the buttons being large enough to touch easily and a layout that is similar to most physical remotes. There are several customizations possible though I have not used them.

With that being said a lot of the remotes work rate I found compatibility on almost everything that works with infrared and there's a surprising amount of rear devices that are actually on here and you get a few options for it long story short you have to fiddle with it and programming the buttons sometimes takes forever but it works and it does exactly what it's told to do and it even has a widget how much better does that get it would be also really cool if there could be like a submarket where I could sell my remote or earn points and sell the remote I built to other people and also download their cooler ones that I didn't spend time working on
